hominum seruator, ‘to preserve men.' The seruator of 1. 877 is picked up by struem in 879, :ut absentem, ‘to observe you.'

882. scincet, ‘of course, rather.' The etymology of the word is sci,· licet, ‘know ; you may do so,’ ‘let me tell you.’ The Latins them- selves seem to have derived it from scire licet, to which of course it corresponds in sense, and in Lucretius we find the full phrase scire licet, and also scilicet, used as its equivalent, 11. 469 scilicet esse globosa, cf. Cic. Att. V. 11. 7. uidelicet (uzde, imperative; licet) has the same history.

uerbeream statuam, ‘that whipping-post statue.’ Pseudolus wishes to emphasise two things: firstly, Simmia’s grand statuesque airs (cf. magnifice), secondly, that he is a worthy subject for stripes (uerbera), which he will probably feel as little as a statue would. Cf. Capt. 946 uerberea statua, Pers. 185 uerbereum caput, As. 360 ulmeus.
